\begin_layout Section
Algorithm for type reduction II
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For a partition 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}=\{G_{1},...,G_{k}\}$
\end_inset

,
 for a set of households 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 define the loss of treating all 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

 as one type as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L(G)=|G|(1-e_{G})
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{G}$
\end_inset

 is CCEI of 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

.
 The total loss of a partition is 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{G\in\mathcal{P}}L(G)$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For each pair of groups 
\begin_inset Formula $G_{a},G_{b}$
\end_inset

,
 calculate the incremental merge cost as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L(G_{a}\cup G_{b})-L(G_{a})-L(G_{b})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Start with the fully rationalizing partition 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}_{K}$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Compute incremental merge cost for every pair of groups
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Merge the pair with the smallest cost
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Recalculate total loss.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
object of interest
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Distortion curve of number of types and total loss.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
At 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 types,
 total loss is 0
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Monotonically decreasing from 1 type to 
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 types
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Algorithm III
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Loss as before,
 but defined as the Varian efficiency vector / average Varian index
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Each observation (household) has its own 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{t}$
\end_inset

 shrinkage factor. 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
L_{Varian}(G)=\sum_{i\in G}(1-e_{i})
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Algorithm IV:
 type schedule (fixed-
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 greedy assignment)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Supersedes Algorithms II and III as the loss exercise.
 Instead of merging the upper-bound partition (so that partitions are nested across 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

),
 rebuild the partition from scratch at every number of types 
\begin_inset Formula $k=1,...,K$
\end_inset

 (
\begin_inset Formula $K$
\end_inset

 the practical upper bound),
 in the style of the C&P upper-bound algorithm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Fix 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

.
 Visit the observations in a random order (one randomized run).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
For each observation 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 and each existing group 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

,
 evaluate the placement of 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $G$
\end_inset

:
 under CCEI,
 the resulting group CCEI 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{G\cup\{i\}}$
\end_inset

;
 under Varian,
 the largest multiplier 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 consistent with the group (existing members keep their multipliers).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
CCEI (max-min,
 matching the reported statistic):
 assign 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 to the placement maximizing the resulting 
\emph on
minimum
\emph default
 group CCEI,
 breaking ties by the host group's resulting CCEI,
 then its size,
 then the lowest label;
 while fewer than 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 groups are open,
 starting a new group is scored as a candidate placement like any other (host CCEI 1,
 other groups untouched).
 This spreads violators across groups;
 a marginal least-harm rule would instead funnel them into whichever group is already worst,
 pinning the minimum near the pooled CCEI.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Varian:
 assign 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 to the group granting the highest 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

,
 ties toward the largest group,
 then the lowest label;
 if every existing group would grant 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}<1$
\end_inset

 and fewer than 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 groups are open,
 
\begin_inset Formula $i$
\end_inset

 starts a new group.
 At 
\begin_inset Formula $k=K$
\end_inset

 this reduces to the C&P practical upper-bound algorithm.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Track each group's CCEI (respectively,
 each observation's multiplier 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

) through the assignment.
 Report,
 for each 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

:
 the 
\emph on
minimum
\emph default
 group CCEI — the common efficiency level at which every group passes 
\begin_inset Formula $e$
\end_inset

-GARP — or the simple average of the 
\begin_inset Formula $e_{i}$
\end_inset

 across all observations.
 (Optionally the Varian multipliers can be re-optimized per group at the end:
 exact via the Demuynck-Rehbeck MILP for small groups,
 coordinate ascent for medium ones.)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\series bold
Properties and object of interest
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Graph of rationality (minimum group CCEI or average Varian multiplier,
 y axis) against the number of types (x axis),
 weakly monotonically increasing.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
The saved upper-bound partition is scored as a candidate at 
\begin_inset Formula $k=K$
\end_inset

,
 so the schedule ends at exactly full rationality.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Partitions are not nested across 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

:
 each 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is rebuilt from scratch.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Itemize
Monotonicity by construction:
 a partition into fewer than 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 groups is feasible when 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 are allowed,
 so whenever the greedy result at 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 is worse than at 
\begin_inset Formula $k-1$
\end_inset

,
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $k-1$
\end_inset

 partition is carried forward.
\end_layout

